chrome-headless.local%3A9222%2Fatomic )

I have been a verified user of Twitter since April 2015, and I=E2=80=99ll t=
ell you how I got it: someone from Twitter emailed or DM=E2=80=99d me about=
 something unrelated, and I asked if I could be verified; a day later I was=
 (Eric Seufert told a similar story on X ( https://x.com/eric_seufert/statu=
s/1811721418394010084 ) ). Granted, I would like to think that I am trustwo=
rthy, but while blue checks were nominally for well-known people and journa=
lists, everyone knew it by-and-large came down to getting a favor from some=
 random Twitter employee; moreover, if there is one thing we have learned o=
ver the last decade it is that blue checks =E2=80=94 particularly to the ex=
tent they move in unison on controversial topics =E2=80=94 hardly have a mo=
nopoly on the truth.

Setting that aside, though, how is the decision of what labels to apply or =
not apply to various accounts the prerogative of E.U. bureaucrats? This is =
the very definition of government making product decisions, and not only is=
 that wrong in principle, it=E2=80=99s also totally unnecessary: the precip=
itating event for X=E2=80=99s dramatic fall-off in advertising revenue was =
the failed roll-out of the new blue-check system, when X allowed users to i=
mpersonate well-known brands like Nintendo ( https://kotaku.com/twitter-blu=
e-verification-nintendo-valve-elon-musk-1849764859 ) or Eli Lilly ( https:/=
/www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2022/11/14/twitter-fake-eli-lilly/ ) ; t=
hat laissez faire approach was rolled back to today=E2=80=99s policy ( http=
s://help.x.com/en/managing-your-account/about-x-verified-accounts ) that re=
quires review for non-deceptiveness (and which includes special badges like=
 Breton=E2=80=99s gray check-mark for being a government official), but the=
 fact remains that X=E2=80=99s potential fine is actually a lot lower than =
that suggested in the excerpt, because the company=E2=80=99s advertising re=
venue has never recovered. That certainly seems like the market is working!

More broadly, one of the the critiques of European economies is how difficu=
lt it is to fire people; while the first-order intentions are obviously und=
erstandable, the critique is that companies underinvest in growth because t=
here is so much risk attached to hiring: if you get the wrong person, or if=
 expected growth doesn=E2=80=99t materialize, you are stuck. What is notabl=
e is how Europe seems to have decided on the same approach to product devel=
opment: Google is expected to have 10 blue links forever, Microsoft can=E2=
=80=99t include a browser or shift the center of gravity of its business to=
 Teams, Apple can=E2=80=99t use user data for Apple Intelligence, and, in t=
his case, X is forever bound to the European Commission=E2=80=99s interpret=
ation of what a blue check meant under previous ownership. Everything, once=
